      <h2>When to Give Up and Buy New Boots</h2>
      <p>Even with perfect maintenance, boots eventually need replacing. Here are the signs:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>The tread is smooth.</strong> If the outsole pattern is worn flat, you've lost slip resistance. This is a safety hazard on wet or sloped surfaces.</li>
        <li><strong>The sole separates from the upper.</strong> If the sole is delaminating more than 1 inch, repair is temporary at best. It's time for new boots.</li>
        <li><strong>The steel or composite toe is exposed.</strong> If the leather has worn through to the toe cap, replace immediately. You've lost the integrity of the boot.</li>
        <li><strong>Cracked leather that leaks.</strong> Once leather cracks all the way through, no amount of conditioning will seal it.</li>
        <li><strong>Persistent foot pain.</strong> If your boots used to be comfortable and now hurt your feet, the structural support is gone. New insoles may help temporarily, but the boot is done.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Summary: Your 3-Minute Daily Boot Care Routine</h2>
      <div style="background:#1a2332;border:1px solid #2a3a4e;border-radius:0.5rem;padding:1.25rem;margin:1.5rem 0">
        <p><strong>🔹 After each shift (2 min):</strong> Brush off debris → Remove insoles → Open laces fully → Store in ventilated area</p>
        <p><strong>🔹 Every Sunday (10 min):</strong> Brush clean → Inspect for damage → Wipe with damp cloth → Condition if dry</p>
        <p><strong>🔹 Every month (20 min):</strong> Deep clean with saddle soap → Dry with newspaper → Condition leather → Waterproof → Replace insoles</p>
        <p><strong>🔹 Every 6 months:</strong> Check with a cobbler for restitching or sole regluing</p>
      </div>
      <p>Follow this routine and your work boots will easily last 18–24 months — saving you hundreds of dollars and keeping your feet safer and more comfortable every shift.</p>

